# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: heterogeneous-catalysis
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] In biology and biochemistry, the **active site** is the region of an enzyme where substrate molecules bind and undergo a chemical reaction.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] The active site consists of amino acid residues that form temporary bonds with the substrate, the *binding site*, and residues that catalyse a reaction of that substrate, the ***catalytic site***.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] Although the active site occupies only ~10–20% of the volume of an enzyme, it is the most important part as it directly catalyzes the chemical reaction.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] It usually consists of three to four amino acids, while other amino acids within the protein are required to maintain the tertiary structure of the enzymes.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] Each active site is evolved to be optimised to bind a particular substrate and catalyse a particular reaction, resulting in high specificity.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] This specificity is determined by the arrangement of amino acids within the active site and the structure of the substrates.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] Sometimes enzymes also need to bind with some cofactors to fulfil their function.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] The active site is usually a groove or pocket of the enzyme which can be located in a deep tunnel within the enzyme, or between the interfaces of multimeric enzymes.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] An active site can catalyse a reaction repeatedly as residues are not altered at the end of the reaction (they may change during the reaction, but are regenerated by the end).
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] This process is achieved by lowering the activation energy of the reaction, so more substrates have enough energy to undergo reaction.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] Usually, an enzyme molecule has only one active site, and the active site fits with one specific type of substrate.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] An active site contains a binding site that binds the substrate and orients it for catalysis.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] The orientation of the substrate and the close proximity between it and the active site is so important that in some cases the enzyme can still function properly even though all other parts are mutated and lose function.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] Initially, the interaction between the active site and the substrate is non-covalent and transient.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] There are four important types of interaction that hold the substrate in a defined orientation and form an enzyme-substrate complex (ES complex): hydrogen bonds, van der Waals interactions, hydrophobic interactions and electrostatic force interactions.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] The charge distribution on the substrate and active site must be complementary, which means all positive and negative charges must be cancelled out.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] Otherwise, there will be a repulsive force pushing them apart.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] The active site usually contains non-polar amino acids, although sometimes polar amino acids may also occur.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] The binding of substrate to the binding site requires at least three contact points in order to achieve stereo-, regio-, and enantioselectivity.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] For example, alcohol dehydrogenase which catalyses the transfer of a hydride ion from ethanol to NAD+ interacts with the substrate methyl group, hydroxyl group and the pro-*(R)* hydrogen that will be abstracted during the reaction.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] In order to exert their function, enzymes need to assume their correct protein fold (*native fold*) and tertiary structure.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] To maintain this defined three-dimensional structure, proteins rely on various types of interactions between their amino acid residues.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] If these interactions are interfered with, for example by extreme pH values, high temperature or high ion concentrations, this will cause the enzyme to denature and lose its catalytic activity.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] A tighter fit between an active site and the substrate molecule is believed to increase the efficiency of a reaction.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] If the tightness between the active site of DNA polymerase and its substrate is increased, the fidelity, which means the correct rate of DNA replication will also increase.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] Most enzymes have deeply buried active sites, which can be accessed by a substrate via access channels.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] There are three proposed models of how enzymes fit their specific substrate: the lock and key model, the induced fit model, and the conformational selection model.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] The latter two are not mutually exclusive: conformational selection can be followed by a change in the enzyme's shape.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] Additionally, a protein may not wholly follow either model.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] Amino acids at the binding site of ubiquitin generally follow the induced fit model, whereas the rest of the protein generally adheres to conformational selection.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] Factors such as temperature likely influences the pathway taken during binding, with higher temperatures predicted to increase the importance of conformational selection and decrease that of induced fit.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] This concept was suggested by the 19th-century chemist Emil Fischer.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] He proposed that the active site and substrate are two stable structures that fit perfectly without any further modification, just like a key fits into a lock.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] If one substrate perfectly binds to its active site, the interactions between them will be strongest, resulting in high catalytic efficiency.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] As time went by, limitations of this model started to appear.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] For example, the competitive enzyme inhibitor methylglucoside can bind tightly to the active site of 4-alpha-glucanotransferase and perfectly fits into it.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] However, 4-alpha-glucanotransferase is not active on methylglucoside and no glycosyl transfer occurs.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] The Lock and Key hypothesis cannot explain this, as it would predict a high efficiency of methylglucoside glycosyl transfer due to its tight binding.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] Apart from competitive inhibition, this theory cannot explain the mechanism of action of non-competitive inhibitors either, as they do not bind to the active site but nevertheless influence catalytic activity.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] Daniel Koshland's theory of enzyme-substrate binding is that the active site and the binding portion of the substrate are not exactly complementary.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] The induced fit model is a development of the lock-and-key model and assumes that an active site is flexible and changes shape until the substrate is completely bound.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] This model is similar to a person wearing a glove: the glove changes shape to fit the hand.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] The enzyme initially has a conformation that attracts its substrate.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] Enzyme surface is flexible and only the correct catalyst can induce interaction leading to catalysis.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] Conformational changes may then occur as the substrate is bound.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] After the reaction products will move away from the enzyme and the active site returns to its initial shape.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] This hypothesis is supported by the observation that the entire protein domain could move several nanometers during catalysis.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] This movement of protein surface can create microenvironments that favour the catalysis.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] This model suggests that enzymes exist in a variety of conformations, only some of which are capable of binding to a substrate.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] When a substrate is bound to the protein, the equilibrium in the conformational ensemble shifts towards those able to bind ligands (as enzymes with bound substrates are removed from the equilibrium between the free conformations).
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] Positively charged sodium ion and negatively charged fluoride ion attract each other to form sodium fluoride under electrostatic interaction.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] Hydrogen bond between two water molecules.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] Van der Waals force between two acetone molecules.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] The lower acetone molecule contains a partially negative oxygen atom that attracts partially positive carbon atom in the upper acetone.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] Hydrophobic and hydrophilic groups tend to assemble with the same kind of molecules.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] Once the substrate is bound and oriented to the active site, catalysis can begin.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] The residues of the catalytic site are typically very close to the binding site, and some residues can have dual-roles in both binding and catalysis.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] During enzyme catalytic reaction, the substrate and active site are brought together in a close proximity.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] Firstly, when substrates bind within the active site the effective concentration of it significantly increases than in solution.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] This means the number of substrate molecules involved in the reaction is also increased.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] This process also reduces the desolvation energy required for the reaction to occur.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] In solution substrate molecules are surrounded by solvent molecules and energy is required for enzyme molecules to replace them and contact with the substrate.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] Since bulk molecules can be excluded from the active site this energy output can be minimised.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] Next, the active site is designed to reorient the substrate to reduce the activation energy for the reaction to occur.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] The alignment of the substrate, after binding, is locked in a high energy state and can proceed to the next step.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] In addition, this binding is favoured by entropy as the energy cost associated with solution reaction is largely eliminated since solvent cannot enter active site.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] In the end, the active site may manipulate the Molecular orbital of the substrate into a suitable orientation to reduce activation energy.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] The electrostatic states of substrate and active site must be complementary to each other.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] A polarized negatively charged amino acid side chain will repel uncharged substrate.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] But if the transition state involves the formation of an ion centre then the side chain will now produce a favourable interaction.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] Many enzymes including serine protease, cysteine protease, protein kinase and phosphatase evolved to form transient covalent bonds between them and their substrates to lower the activation energy and allow the reaction to occur.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] This process can be divided into 2 steps: formation and breakdown.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] The former step is rate-limit step while the later step is needed to regenerate intact enzyme.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] Metal ions have multiple roles during the reaction.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] Firstly it can bind to negatively charged substrate groups so they will not repel electron pairs from active site's nucleophilic groups.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] It can attract negatively charged electrons to increase electrophilicity.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] It can also bridge between active site and substrate.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] At last, they may change the conformational structure of the substrate to favour reaction.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] In some reactions, protons and hydroxide may directly act as acid and base in term of specific acid and specific base catalysis.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] But more often groups in substrate and active site act as Brønsted–Lowry acid and base.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] This is called general acid and general base theory.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] The easiest way to distinguish between them is to check whether the reaction rate is determined by the concentrations of the general acid and base.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] If the answer is yes then the reaction is the general type.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] Since most enzymes have an optimum pH of 6 to 7, the amino acids in the side chain usually have a p*K*a of 4~10.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] Candidate include aspartate, glutamate, histidine, cysteine.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] These acids and bases can stabilise the nucleophile or electrophile formed during the catalysis by providing positive and negative charges.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] Quantitative studies of enzymatic reactions often found that the acceleration of chemical reaction speed cannot be fully explained by existing theories like the approximation, acid/base catalysis and electrophile/nucleophile catalysis.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] And there is an obvious paradox: in reversible enzymatic reaction if the active site perfectly fits the substrates then the backward reaction will be slowed since products cannot fit perfectly into the active site.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] So conformational distortion was introduced and argues that both active site and substrate can undergo conformational changes to fit with each other all the time.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] This theory is a little similar to the Lock and Key Theory, but at this time the active site is preprogrammed to bind perfectly to substrate in transition state rather than in ground state.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] The formation of transition state within the solution requires a large amount of energy to relocate solvent molecules and the reaction is slowed.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] So the active site can substitute solvent molecules and surround the substrates to minimize the counterproductive effect imposed by the solution.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] The presence of charged groups with the active site will attract substrates and ensure electrostatic complementarity.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] In reality, most enzyme mechanisms involve a combination of several different types of catalysis.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] The role of glutathione(GSH) is to remove accumulated reactive oxygen species which may damage cells.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] During this process, its thiol side chain is oxidised and two glutathione molecules are connected by a disulphide bond to form a dimer(GSSG).
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] In order to regenerate glutathione the disulphide bond has to be broken, In human cells, this is done by glutathione reductase(GR).
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] Glutathione reductase is a dimer that contains two identical subunits.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] It requires one NADP and one FAD as the cofactors.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] The active site is located in the linkage between two subunits.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] The NADPH is involved in the generation of FADH-.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] In the active site, there are two cysteine residues besides the FAD cofactor and are used to break the disulphide bond during the catalytic reaction.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] NADPH is bound by three positively charged residues: Arg-218, His-219 and Arg-224.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] The catalytic process starts when the FAD is reduced by NADPH to accept one electron and from FADH−.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] It then attacks the disulphide bond formed between 2 cysteine residues, forming one SH bond and a single S− group.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] This S− group will act as a nucleophile to attack the disulphide bond in the oxidised glutathione(GSSG), breaking it and forming a cysteine-SG complex.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] The first SG− anion is released and then receives one proton from adjacent SH group and from the first glutathione monomer.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] Next the adjacent S− group attack disulphide bond in cysteine-SG complex and release the second SG− anion.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] It receives one proton in solution and forms the second glutathione monomer.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] Chymotrypsin is a serine endopeptidase that is present in pancreatic juice and helps the hydrolysis of proteins and peptide.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] It catalyzes the hydrolysis of peptide bonds in L-isomers of tyrosine, phenylalanine, and tryptophan.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] In the active site of this enzyme, three amino acid residues work together to form a catalytic triad which makes up the catalytic site.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] In chymotrypsin, these residues are Ser-195, His-57 and Asp-102.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] The mechanism of chymotrypsin can be divided into two phases.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] First, Ser-195 nucleophilically attacks the peptide bond carbon in the substrate to form a tetrahedral intermediate.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] The nucleophilicity of Ser-195 is enhanced by His-57, which abstracts a proton from Ser-195 and is in turn stabilised by the negatively charged carboxylate group (RCOO−) in Asp-102.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] Furthermore, the tetrahedral oxyanion intermediate generated in this step is stabilised by hydrogen bonds from Ser-195 and Gly-193.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] In the second stage, the R'NH group is protonated by His-57 to form R'NH2 and leaves the intermediate, leaving behind the acylated Ser-195.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] His-57 then acts as a base again to abstract one proton from a water molecule.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] The resulting hydroxide anion nucleophilically attacks the acyl-enzyme complex to form a second tetrahedral oxyanion intermediate, which is once again stabilised by H bonds.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] In the end, Ser-195 leaves the tetrahedral intermediate, breaking the CO bond that connected the enzyme to the peptide substrate.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] A proton is transferred to Ser-195 through His-57, so that all three amino acid return to their initial state.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] Substrate unbinding is influenced by various factors.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] Larger ligands generally stay in the active site longer, as do those with more rotatable bonds (although this may be a side effect of size).
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] When the solvent is excluded from the active site, less flexible proteins result in longer residence times.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] More hydrogen bonds shielded from the solvent also decrease unbinding.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] Enzymes can use cofactors as 'helper molecules'.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] Coenzymes are referred to those non-protein molecules that bind with enzymes to help them fulfill their jobs.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] Mostly they are connected to the active site by non-covalent bonds such as hydrogen bond or hydrophobic interaction.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] But sometimes a covalent bond can also form between them.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] For example, the heme in cytochrome C is bound to the protein through thioester bond.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] In some occasions, coenzymes can leave enzymes after the reaction is finished.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] Otherwise, they permanently bind to the enzyme.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] Coenzyme is a broad concept which includes metal ions, various vitamins and ATP.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] If an enzyme needs coenzyme to work itself, it is called an apoenzyme.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] In fact, it alone cannot catalyze reactions properly.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] Only when its cofactor comes in and binds to the active site to form holoenzyme does it work properly.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] It contains a distinct conjugated isoalloxazine ring system.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] Flavin has multiple redox states and can be used in processes that involve the transfer of one or two electrons.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] It can act as an electron acceptor in reaction, like the oxidation of NAD to NADH, to accept two electrons and form 1,5-dihydroflavin.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] On the other hand, it can form semiquinone(free radical) by accepting one electron, and then converts to fully reduced form by the addition of an extra electron.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] This property allows it to be used in one electron oxidation process.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] Inhibitors disrupt the interaction between enzyme and substrate, slowing down the rate of a reaction.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] There are different types of inhibitor, including both reversible and irreversible forms.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] Competitive inhibitors are inhibitors that only target free enzyme molecules.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] They compete with substrates for free enzyme acceptor and can be overcome by increasing the substrate concentration.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] Competitive inhibitors usually have structural similarities to the substrates and or ES complex.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] As a result, they can fit into the active site and trigger favourable interactions to fill in the space and block substrates from entry.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] They can also induce transient conformational changes in the active site so substrates cannot fit perfectly with it.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] After a short period of time, competitive inhibitors will drop off and leave the enzyme intact.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] Inhibitors are classified as non-competitive inhibitors when they bind both free enzyme and ES complex.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] Since they do not compete with substrates for the active site, they cannot be overcome by simply increasing the substrate concentration.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] They usually bind to a different site on the enzyme and alter the 3-dimensional structure of the active site to block substrates from entry or leaving the enzyme.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] Irreversible inhibitors are similar to competitive inhibitors as they both bind to the active site.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] However, irreversible inhibitors form irreversible covalent bonds with the amino acid residues in the active site and never leave.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] Therefore, the active site is occupied and the substrate cannot enter.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] Occasionally the inhibitor will leave but the catalytic site is permanently altered in shape.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] These inhibitors usually contain electrophilic groups like halogen substitutes and epoxides.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] As time goes by more and more enzymes are bound by irreversible inhibitors and cannot function anymore.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] HIV protease inhibitors are used to treat patients having AIDS virus by preventing its DNA replication.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] HIV protease is used by the virus to cleave Gag-Pol polyprotein into 3 smaller proteins that are responsible for virion assembly, package and maturation.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] This enzyme targets the specific phenylalanine-proline cleave site within the target protein.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] If HIV protease is switched off the virion particle will lose function and cannot infect patients.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] Since it is essential in viral replication and is absent in healthy human, it is an ideal target for drug development.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] HIV protease belongs to aspartic protease family and has a similar mechanism.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] Firstly the aspartate residue activates a water molecule and turns it into a nucleophile.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] Then it attacks the carbonyl group within the peptide bond (NH-CO) to form a tetrahedral intermediate.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] The nitrogen atom within the intermediate receives a proton, forming an amide group and subsequent rearrangement leads to the breakdown of the bond between it and the intermediate and forms two products.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] Inhibitors usually contain a nonhydrolyzable hydroxyethylene or hydroxyethylamine groups that mimic the tetrahedral intermediate.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] Since they share a similar structure and electrostatic arrangement to the transition state of substrates they can still fit into the active site but cannot be broken down, so hydrolysis cannot occur.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] Strychnine is a neurotoxin that causes death by affecting nerves that control muscular contraction and cause respiration difficulty.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] The impulse is transmitted between the synapse through a neurotransmitter called acetylcholine.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] It is released into the synapse between nerve cells and binds to receptors in the postsynaptic cell.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] Then an action potential is generated and transmitted through the postsynaptic cell to start a new cycle.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] Glycine can inhibit the activity of neurotransmitter receptors, thus a larger amount of acetylcholinesterase is required to trigger an action potential.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] This makes sure that the generation of nerve impulses is tightly controlled.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] However, this control is broken down when strychnine is added.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] It inhibits glycine receptors(a chloride channel) and a much lower level of neurotransmitter concentration can trigger an action potential.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] Nerves now constantly transmit signals and cause excessive muscular contraction, leading to asphyxiation and death.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] Diisopropyl fluorophosphate (DIFP) is an irreversible inhibitor that blocks the action of serine protease.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] When it binds to the enzyme a nucleophilic substitution reaction occurs and releases one hydrogen fluoride molecule.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] The OH group in the active site acts as a nucleophile to attack the phosphorus in DIFP and form a tetrahedral intermediate and release a proton.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] Then the P-F bond is broken, one electron is transferred to the F atom and it leaves the intermediate as F− anion.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] It combines with a proton in solution to form one HF molecule.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] A covalent bond formed between the active site and DIFP, so the serine side chain is no longer available to the substrate.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] Identification of active sites is crucial in the process of drug discovery.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] The 3-D structure of the enzyme is analysed to identify active site residues and design drugs which can fit into them.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] Proteolytic enzymes are targets for some drugs, such as protease inhibitors, which include drugs against AIDS and hypertension.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] These protease inhibitors bind to an enzyme's active site and block interaction with natural substrates.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] An important factor in drug design is the strength of binding between the active site and an enzyme inhibitor.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] If the enzyme found in bacteria is significantly different from the human enzyme then an inhibitor can be designed against that particular bacterium without harming the human enzyme.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] If one kind of enzyme is only present in one kind of organism, its inhibitor can be used to specifically wipe them out.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] Active sites can be mapped to aid the design of new drugs such as enzyme inhibitors.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] This involves the description of the size of an active site and the number and properties of sub-sites, such as details of the binding interaction.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] Modern database technology called CPASS (Comparison of Protein Active Site Structures) however allows the comparison of active sites in more detail and the finding of structural similarity using software.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] An allosteric site is a site on an enzyme, unrelated to its active site, which can bind an effector molecule.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] This interaction is another mechanism of enzyme regulation.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] Allosteric modification usually happens in proteins with more than one subunit.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] Allosteric interactions are often present in metabolic pathways and are beneficial in that they allow one step of a reaction to regulate another step.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/active-site] They allow an enzyme to have a range of molecular interactions, other than the highly specific active site.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] Like surface tension, adsorption is a consequence of surface energy.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] In a bulk material, all the bonding requirements (be they ionic, covalent, or metallic) of the constituent atoms of the material are fulfilled by other atoms in the material.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] However, atoms on the surface of the adsorbent are not wholly surrounded by other adsorbent atoms and therefore can attract adsorbates.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] The exact nature of the bonding depends on the details of the species involved, but the adsorption process is generally classified as physisorption (characteristic of weak van der Waals forces) or chemisorption (characteristic of covalent bonding).
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] It may also occur due to electrostatic attraction.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] The nature of the adsorption can affect the structure of the adsorbed species.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] For example, polymer physisorption from solution can result in squashed structures on a surface.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] Adsorption, ion exchange, and chromatography are sorption processes in which certain adsorbates are selectively transferred from the fluid phase to the surface of insoluble, rigid particles suspended in a vessel or packed in a column.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] Pharmaceutical industry applications, which use adsorption as a means to prolong neurological exposure to specific drugs or parts thereof, are lesser known.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] The word "adsorption" was coined in 1881 by German physicist Heinrich Kayser (1853–1940).
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] The adsorption of gases and solutes is usually described through isotherms, that is, the amount of adsorbate on the adsorbent as a function of its pressure (if gas) or concentration (for liquid phase solutes) at constant temperature.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] The quantity adsorbed is nearly always normalized by the mass of the adsorbent to allow comparison of different materials.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] A number of different isotherm models have been developed.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] where x is the mass of adsorbate adsorbed, m is the mass of the adsorbent, P is the pressure of adsorbate (this can be changed to concentration if investigating solution rather than gas), and k and n are empirical constants for each adsorbent–adsorbate pair at a given temperature.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] The function is not adequate at very high pressure because in reality $x/m$ has an asymptotic maximum as pressure increases without bound.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] As the temperature increases, the constants k and n change to reflect the empirical observation that the quantity adsorbed rises more slowly and higher pressures are required to saturate the surface.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] Irving Langmuir was the first to derive a scientifically based adsorption isotherm in 1918.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] The model applies to gases adsorbed on solid surfaces.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] It is a semi-empirical isotherm with a kinetic basis and was derived based on statistical thermodynamics.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] It is the most common isotherm equation to use due to its simplicity and its ability to fit a variety of adsorption data.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] The surface is energetically homogeneous, and adsorbed molecules do not interact.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] At the maximum adsorption, only a monolayer is formed.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] Adsorption only occurs on localized sites on the surface, not with other adsorbates.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] These four assumptions are seldom all true: there are always imperfections on the surface, adsorbed molecules are not necessarily inert, and the mechanism is clearly not the same for the first molecules to adsorb to a surface as for the last.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] The fourth condition is the most troublesome, as frequently more molecules will adsorb to the monolayer; this problem is addressed by the BET isotherm for relatively flat (non-microporous) surfaces.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] The Langmuir isotherm is nonetheless the first choice for most models of adsorption and has many applications in surface kinetics (usually called Langmuir–Hinshelwood kinetics) and thermodynamics.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] Langmuir suggested that adsorption takes place through this mechanism: $A_{\text{g}}+S\rightleftharpoons AS$ , where *A* is a gas molecule, and *S* is an adsorption site.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] The direct and inverse rate constants are *k* and *k*−1.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] where P is the partial pressure of the gas or the molar concentration of the solution.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] For very low pressures $\theta \approx KP$ , and for high pressures $\theta \approx 1$ .
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] The value of $\theta$ is difficult to measure experimentally; usually, the adsorbate is a gas and the quantity adsorbed is given in moles, grams, or gas volumes at standard temperature and pressure (STP) per gram of adsorbent.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] Through its slope and *y* intercept we can obtain *v*mon and *K*, which are constants for each adsorbent–adsorbate pair at a given temperature.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] *v*mon is related to the number of adsorption sites through the ideal gas law.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] If we assume that the number of sites is just the whole area of the solid divided into the cross section of the adsorbate molecules, we can easily calculate the surface area of the adsorbent.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] The surface area of an adsorbent depends on its structure: the more pores it has, the greater the area, which has a big influence on reactions on surfaces.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] where *i* is each one of the gases that adsorb.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] 1) To choose between the Langmuir and Freundlich equations, the enthalpies of adsorption must be investigated.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] While the Langmuir model assumes that the energy of adsorption remains constant with surface occupancy, the Freundlich equation is derived with the assumption that the heat of adsorption continually decrease as the binding sites are occupied.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] The choice of the model based on best fitting of the data is a common misconception.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] 2) The use of the linearized form of the Langmuir model is no longer common practice.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] Advances in computational power allowed for nonlinear regression to be performed quickly and with higher confidence since no data transformation is required.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] Often molecules do form multilayers, that is, some are adsorbed on already adsorbed molecules, and the Langmuir isotherm is not valid.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] In 1938 Stephen Brunauer, Paul Emmett, and Edward Teller developed a model isotherm that takes that possibility into account.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] Their theory is called BET theory, after the initials in their last names.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] The derivation of the formula is more complicated than Langmuir's (see links for complete derivation).
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] The key assumption used in deriving the BET equation that the successive heats of adsorption for all layers except the first are equal to the heat of condensation of the adsorbate.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] The Langmuir isotherm is usually better for chemisorption, and the BET isotherm works better for physisorption for non-microporous surfaces.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] In other instances, molecular interactions between gas molecules previously adsorbed on a solid surface form significant interactions with gas molecules in the gaseous phases.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] Hence, adsorption of gas molecules to the surface is more likely to occur around gas molecules that are already present on the solid surface, rendering the Langmuir adsorption isotherm ineffective for the purposes of modelling.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] This effect was studied in a system where nitrogen was the adsorbate and tungsten was the adsorbent by Paul Kisliuk (1922–2008) in 1957.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] To compensate for the increased probability of adsorption occurring around molecules present on the substrate surface, Kisliuk developed the precursor state theory, whereby molecules would enter a precursor state at the interface between the solid adsorbent and adsorbate in the gaseous phase.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] From here, adsorbate molecules would either adsorb to the adsorbent or desorb into the gaseous phase.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] The probability of adsorption occurring from the precursor state is dependent on the adsorbate's proximity to other adsorbate molecules that have already been adsorbed.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] If an adsorbate molecule enters the precursor state at a location that is remote from any other previously adsorbed adsorbate molecules, the sticking probability is reflected by the size of the SD constant.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] As SD is dictated by factors that are taken into account by the Langmuir model, SD can be assumed to be the adsorption rate constant.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] However, the rate constant for the Kisliuk model (*R*') is different from that of the Langmuir model, as *R*' is used to represent the impact of diffusion on monolayer formation and is proportional to the square root of the system's diffusion coefficient.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] As can be seen in the formula, the variation of *K* must be isosteric, that is, at constant coverage.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] that is to say, adsorption is more exothermic than liquefaction.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] The adsorption of ensemble molecules on a surface or interface can be divided into two processes: adsorption and desorption.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] If the adsorption rate wins the desorption rate, the molecules will accumulate over time giving the adsorption curve over time.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] If the desorption rate is larger, the number of molecules on the surface will decrease over time.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] The adsorption rate is dependent on the temperature, the diffusion rate of the solute (related to mean free path for pure gas), and the energy barrier between the molecule and the surface.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] The diffusion and key elements of the adsorption rate can be calculated using Fick's laws of diffusion and the Einstein relation (kinetic theory).
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] where A is the surface area (unit m2), C is the number concentration of the molecule in the bulk solution (unit #/m3), D is the diffusion constant (unit m2/s), and t is time (unit s).
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] Further simulations and analysis of this equation show that the square root dependence on the time is originated from the decrease of the concentrations near the surface under ideal adsorption conditions.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] Also, this equation only works for the beginning of the adsorption when a well-behaved concentration gradient forms near the surface.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] Correction on the reduction of the adsorption area and slowing down of the concentration gradient evolution have to be considered over a longer time.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] Under real experimental conditions, the flow and the small adsorption area always make the adsorption rate faster than what this equation predicted, and the energy barrier will either accelerate this rate by surface attraction or slow it down by surface repulsion.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] Thus, the prediction from this equation is often a few to several orders of magnitude away from the experimental results.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] The desorption of a molecule from the surface depends on the binding energy of the molecule to the surface and the temperature.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] The typical overall adsorption rate is thus often a combined result of the adsorption and desorption.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] Since 1980 two theories were worked on to explain adsorption and obtain equations that work.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] These two are referred to as the chi hypothesis, the quantum mechanical derivation, and excess surface work (ESW).
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] where "ads" stands for "adsorbed", "m" stands for "monolayer equivalence" and "vap" is reference to the vapor pressure of the liquid adsorptive at the same temperature as the solid sample.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] The plot of $n_{ads}$ adsorbed versus $\chi$ is referred to as the chi plot.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] For flat surfaces, the slope of the chi plot yields the surface area.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] Empirically, this plot was noticed as being a very good fit to the isotherm by Michael Polanyi and also by Jan Hendrik de Boer and Cornelis Zwikker but not pursued.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] This was due to criticism in the former case by Albert Einstein and in the latter case by Brunauer.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] This flat surface equation may be used as a "standard curve" in the normal tradition of comparison curves, with the exception that the porous sample's early portion of the plot of $n_{ads}$ versus $\chi$ acts as a self-standard.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] Ultramicroporous, microporous, and mesoporous conditions may be analyzed using this technique.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] Typical standard deviations for full isotherm fits including porous samples are less than 2%.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] Notice that in this description of physical adsorption, the entropy of adsorption is consistent with the Dubinin thermodynamic criterion, that is the entropy of adsorption from the liquid state to the adsorbed state is approximately zero.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] Adsorbents are used usually in the form of spherical pellets, rods, moldings, or monoliths with a hydrodynamic radius between 0.25 and 5 millimetres (0.0098 and 0.1969 in).
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] They must have high abrasion resistance, high thermal stability, and small pore diameters, which results in higher exposed surface area and hence high capacity for adsorption.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] The adsorbents must also have a distinct pore structure that enables fast transport of the gaseous vapors.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] Silica gel is a chemically inert, non-toxic, polar, and dimensionally stable (< 400 °C or 750 °F) amorphous form of SiO2.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] It is prepared by the reaction between sodium silicate and acetic acid, which is followed by a series of after-treatment processes such as aging, pickling, etc.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] These after-treatment methods results in various pore size distributions.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] Silica is used for drying of process air (e.g. oxygen, natural gas) and adsorption of heavy (polar) hydrocarbons from natural gas.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] Zeolites are natural or synthetic crystalline aluminosilicates, which have a repeating pore network and release water at high temperature.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] They are manufactured by hydrothermal synthesis of sodium aluminosilicate or another silica source in an autoclave followed by ion exchange with certain cations (Na+, Li+, Ca2+, K+, NH4+).
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] The channel diameter of zeolite cages usually ranges from 2 to 9 Å.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] The ion exchange process is followed by drying of the crystals, which can be pelletized with a binder to form macroporous pellets.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] Zeolites are applied in drying of process air, CO2 removal from natural gas, CO removal from reforming gas, air separation, catalytic cracking, and catalytic synthesis and reforming.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] Non-polar (siliceous) zeolites are synthesized from aluminum-free silica sources or by dealumination of aluminum-containing zeolites.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] The dealumination process is done by treating the zeolite with steam at elevated temperatures, typically greater than 500 °C (930 °F).
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] This high-temperature heat treatment breaks the aluminum-oxygen bonds and the aluminum atom is expelled from the zeolite framework.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] The term "adsorption" itself was coined by Heinrich Kayser in 1881 in the context of uptake of gases by carbons.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] Activated carbon is a highly porous, amorphous solid consisting of microcrystallites with a graphite lattice, usually prepared in small pellets or a powder.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] One of its main drawbacks is that it reacts with oxygen at moderate temperatures (over 300 °C (572 °F)).
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] Activated carbon can be manufactured from carbonaceous material, including coal (bituminous, subbituminous, and lignite), peat, wood, or nutshells (e.g., coconut).
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] The manufacturing process consists of two phases: carbonization and activation.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] The carbonization process includes drying and then heating to separate by-products, including tars and other hydrocarbons from the raw material, as well as to drive off any gases generated.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] The process is completed by heating the material over 400 °C (750 °F) in an oxygen-free atmosphere that cannot support combustion.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] The carbonized particles are then "activated" by exposing them to an oxidizing agent, usually steam or carbon dioxide, at high temperature.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] This agent burns off the pore-blocking structures created during the carbonization phase, and so they develop a porous, three-dimensional graphite lattice structure.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] The size of the pores developed during activation is a function of the time that they spend in this stage.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] Longer exposure times result in larger pore sizes.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] The most popular aqueous phase carbons are bituminous based because of their hardness, abrasion resistance, pore size distribution, and low cost, but their effectiveness needs to be tested in each application to determine the optimal product.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] Activated carbon is used for adsorption of organic substances and non-polar adsorbates and it is also usually used for waste gas (and waste water) treatment.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] It is the most widely used adsorbent since most of its chemical (e.g. surface groups) and physical properties (e.g. pore size distribution and surface area) can be tuned according to what is needed.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] Its usefulness also derives from its large micropore (and sometimes mesopore) volume and the resulting high surface area.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] Recent research works reported activated carbon as an effective agent to adsorb cationic species of toxic metals from multi-pollutant systems and also proposed possible adsorption mechanisms with supporting evidences.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] The adsorption of water at surfaces is of broad importance in chemical engineering, materials science, and catalysis.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] Also termed surface hydration, the presence of physically or chemically adsorbed water at the surfaces of solids plays an important role in governing interface properties, chemical reaction pathways, and catalytic performance in a wide range of systems.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] In the case of physically adsorbed water, surface hydration can be eliminated simply through drying at conditions of temperature and pressure allowing full vaporization of water.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] The low cost ($200/ton) and high cycle rate (2,000 ×) of synthetic zeolites such as Linde 13X with water adsorbate has garnered much academic and commercial interest recently for use for thermal energy storage (TES), specifically of low-grade solar and waste heat.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] Several pilot projects have been funded in the EU from 2000 to the present (2020).
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] The basic concept is to store solar thermal energy as chemical latent energy in the zeolite.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] Typically, hot dry air from flat plate solar collectors is made to flow through a bed of zeolite such that any water adsorbate present is driven off.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] Storage can be diurnal, weekly, monthly, or even seasonal depending on the volume of the zeolite and the area of the solar thermal panels.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] When heat is called for during the night, or sunless hours, or winter, humidified air flows through the zeolite.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] As the humidity is adsorbed by the zeolite, heat is released to the air and subsequently to the building space.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] This form of TES, with specific use of zeolites, was first taught by John Guerra in 1978.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] Typical adsorbents proposed for carbon capture and storage are zeolites and MOFs.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] The customization of adsorbents makes them a potentially attractive alternative to absorption.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] Because adsorbents can be regenerated by temperature or pressure swing, this step can be less energy intensive than absorption regeneration methods.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] Major problems that are present with adsorption cost in carbon capture are: regenerating the adsorbent, mass ratio, solvent/MOF, cost of adsorbent, production of the adsorbent, lifetime of adsorbent.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] In sorption enhanced water gas shift (SEWGS) technology a pre-combustion carbon capture process, based on solid adsorption, is combined with the water-gas shift reaction (WGS) in order to produce a high pressure hydrogen stream.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] The CO2 stream produced can be stored or used for other industrial processes.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] Protein adsorption is a process that has a fundamental role in the field of biomaterials.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] Indeed, biomaterial surfaces in contact with biological media, such as blood or serum, are immediately coated by proteins.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] Therefore, living cells do not interact directly with the biomaterial surface, but with the adsorbed proteins layer.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] This protein layer mediates the interaction between biomaterials and cells, translating biomaterial physical and chemical properties into a "biological language".
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] In fact, cell membrane receptors bind to protein layer bioactive sites and these receptor-protein binding events are transduced, through the cell membrane, in a manner that stimulates specific intracellular processes that then determine cell adhesion, shape, growth, and differentiation.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] Protein adsorption is influenced by many surface properties such as surface wettability, surface chemical composition, and surface nanometre-scale morphology.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] Surfactant adsorption is a similar phenomenon, but utilising surfactant molecules in the place of proteins.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] Combining an adsorbent with a refrigerant, adsorption chillers use heat to provide a cooling effect.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] This heat, in the form of hot water, may come from any number of industrial sources including waste heat from industrial processes, prime heat from solar thermal installations or from the exhaust or water jacket heat of a piston engine or turbine.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] Although there are similarities between adsorption chillers and absorption refrigeration, the former is based on the interaction between gases and solids.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] The adsorption chamber of the chiller is filled with a solid material (for example zeolite, silica gel, alumina, active carbon or certain types of metal salts), which in its neutral state has adsorbed the refrigerant.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] When heated, the solid desorbs (releases) refrigerant vapour, which subsequently is cooled and liquefied.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] This liquid refrigerant then provides a cooling effect at the evaporator from its enthalpy of vaporization.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] In the final stage the refrigerant vapour is (re)adsorbed into the solid.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] As an adsorption chiller requires no compressor, it is relatively quiet.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] Portal site mediated adsorption is a model for site-selective activated gas adsorption in metallic catalytic systems that contain a variety of different adsorption sites.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] In such systems, low-coordination "edge and corner" defect-like sites can exhibit significantly lower adsorption enthalpies than high-coordination (basal plane) sites.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] As a result, these sites can serve as "portals" for very rapid adsorption to the rest of the surface.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] The phenomenon relies on the common "spillover" effect (described below), where certain adsorbed species exhibit high mobility on some surfaces.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] The model explains seemingly inconsistent observations of gas adsorption thermodynamics and kinetics in catalytic systems where surfaces can exist in a range of coordination structures, and it has been successfully applied to bimetallic catalytic systems where synergistic activity is observed.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] In contrast to pure spillover, portal site adsorption refers to surface diffusion to adjacent adsorption sites, not to non-adsorptive support surfaces.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] The model appears to have been first proposed for carbon monoxide on silica-supported platinum by Brandt *et al.* (1993).
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] A similar, but independent model was developed by King and co-workers to describe hydrogen adsorption on silica-supported alkali promoted ruthenium, silver-ruthenium, and copper-ruthenium bimetallic catalysts.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] The same group applied the model to CO hydrogenation (Fischer–Tropsch synthesis).
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] Zupanc *et al.* (2002) subsequently confirmed the same model for hydrogen adsorption on magnesia-supported caesium-ruthenium bimetallic catalysts.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] Trens *et al.* (2009) have similarly described CO surface diffusion on carbon-supported Pt particles of varying morphology.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] The presence of the metal serves as a lower-energy pathway for gaseous species to first adsorb to the metal and then diffuse on the support surface.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] This is possible because the adsorbed species attains a lower energy state once it has adsorbed to the metal, thus lowering the activation barrier between the gas phase species and the support-adsorbed species.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] Hydrogen spillover is the most common example of an adsorptive spillover.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] In the case of hydrogen, adsorption is most often accompanied with dissociation of molecular hydrogen (H2) to atomic hydrogen (H), followed by spillover of the hydrogen atoms present.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] The spillover effect has been used to explain many observations in heterogeneous catalysis and adsorption.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] Adsorption of molecules onto polymer surfaces is central to a number of applications, including development of non-stick coatings and in various biomedical devices.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] Polymers may also be adsorbed to surfaces through polyelectrolyte adsorption.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] Adsorption is the beginning of viral entry, which is the earliest stage of infection in the viral life cycle.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] The next steps are penetration, uncoating, synthesis (transcription if needed, and translation), and release.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] The virus replication cycle, in this respect, is similar for all types of viruses.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] Factors such as transcription may or may not be needed if the virus is able to integrate its genomic information in the cell's nucleus, or if the virus can replicate itself directly within the cell's cytoplasm.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] The game of *Tetris* is a puzzle game in which blocks of 4 are adsorbed onto a surface during game play.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/adsorption] Scientists have used *Tetris* blocks "as a proxy for molecules with a complex shape" and their "adsorption on a flat surface" for studying the thermodynamics of nanoparticles.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] A **catalytic converter** is an exhaust emission control device which converts toxic gases and pollutants in exhaust gas from an internal combustion engine into less-toxic pollutants by catalyzing a redox reaction.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] Catalytic converters are usually used with internal combustion engines fueled by gasoline (petrol) or diesel, including lean-burn engines, and sometimes on kerosene heaters and stoves.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] The first widespread introduction of catalytic converters was in the United States automobile market.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] To comply with the US Environmental Protection Agency's stricter regulation of exhaust emissions, most gasoline-powered vehicles starting with the 1975 model year are equipped with catalytic converters.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] These "two-way" oxidation converters combine oxygen with carbon monoxide (CO) and unburned hydrocarbons (HC) to produce carbon dioxide (CO2) and water (H2O).
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] "Three-way" converters, which also reduce oxides of nitrogen (NO*x*), were first commercialized by Volvo on the California-specification 1977 240 cars.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] When U.S. federal emission control regulations began requiring tight control of NOx for the 1981 model year, most all automakers met the tighter standards with three-way catalytic converters and associated engine control systems.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] Oxidation-only two-way converters are still used on lean-burn engines to oxidize particulate matter and hydrocarbon emissions (including diesel engines, which typically use lean combustion), as three-way-converters require fuel-rich or stoichiometric combustion to successfully reduce NO*x*.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] Although catalytic converters are most commonly applied to exhaust systems in automobiles, they are also used on electrical generators, forklifts, mining equipment, trucks, buses, locomotives, motorcycles, and on ships.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] Rarely, devices similar to catalytic converters are used in appliances such as wood stoves to control emissions.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] Catalytic converter prototypes were first designed in France at the end of the 19th century, when only a few thousand "oil cars" were on the roads; these prototypes had inert clay-based materials coated with platinum, rhodium, and palladium and sealed into a double metallic cylinder.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] A few decades later, a catalytic converter was patented by Eugene Houdry, a French mechanical engineer.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] Houdry was an expert in catalytic oil refining, having invented the catalytic cracking process that all modern refining is based on today.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] Houdry moved to the United States in 1930 to live near the refineries in Philadelphia and develop his catalytic refining process.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] When the results of early studies of smog in Los Angeles were published, Houdry became concerned about the role of smokestack exhaust and automobile exhaust in air pollution and founded a company called Oxy-Catalyst.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] Houdry first developed catalytic converters for smokestacks, and later developed catalytic converters for warehouse forklifts running on unleaded gasoline.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] In the mid-1950s, he began research to develop catalytic converters for gasoline engines used on cars and was awarded United States Patent 2,742,437 for his work.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] Catalytic converters were further developed by a series of engineers including Carl D.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] Mooney, Antonio Eleazar, and Phillip Messina at Engelhard Corporation, creating the first production catalytic converter in 1973.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] Environmental Protection Agency's new exhaust emissions regulations, most gasoline-powered vehicles manufactured from 1975 onwards are equipped with catalytic converters.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] Early catalytic converters were "two-way", combining oxygen with carbon monoxide (CO) and unburned hydrocarbons (HC, chemical compounds in fuel of the form CmHn) to produce carbon dioxide (CO2) and water (H2O).
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] These stringent emission control regulations also resulted in the removal of the antiknock agent tetraethyl lead from automotive gasoline, to reduce lead in the air.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] Lead and its compounds are catalyst poisons and foul catalytic converters by coating the catalyst's surface.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] Requiring the removal of lead allowed the use of catalytic converters to meet the other emission standards in the regulations.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] To lower harmful NO*x* emissions, a twin-catalyst system was developed in the 1970s – this added a separate (rhodium/platinum) catalyst which reduced NO*x* ahead of the air pump, after which a two-way catalytic converter (palladium/platinum) removed HC and CO.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] This cumbersome and expensive system was soon made redundant, after it was noted that under some conditions the initial catalyst also removed HC and CO.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] This led to the development of the three-way catalyst, made possible by electronics and engine management developments.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] Pfefferle developed a catalytic combustor for gas turbines in the early 1970s, allowing combustion without significant formation of nitrogen oxides and carbon monoxide.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] Four-way catalytic converters have also been developed which also remove particulates from engine exhaust; since most of these particulates are unburned hydrocarbons, they can be burned to convert them into carbon dioxide.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] A washcoat is a carrier for the catalytic materials and is used to disperse the materials over a large surface area.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] Aluminum oxide, titanium dioxide, silicon dioxide e.g. colloidal silica or a mixture of silica and alumina can be used.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] The catalytic materials are suspended in the washcoat prior to applying to the core.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] Washcoat materials are selected to form a rough, irregular surface, which increases the surface area compared to the smooth surface of the bare substrate.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] These oxides are mainly added as oxygen storage promoters.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] The catalyst itself is most often a mix of precious metals, mostly from the platinum group.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] Platinum is the most active catalyst and is widely used, but is not suitable for all applications because of unwanted additional reactions and historically high cost.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] Palladium and rhodium are two other precious metals used, though as of February 2023, platinum has become the least expensive of the platinum group metals.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] Rhodium is used as a reduction catalyst, palladium is used as an oxidation catalyst, and platinum is used both for reduction and oxidation.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] Cerium, iron, manganese, and nickel are also used, although each has limitations.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] Copper can also be used in most countries.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] Nickel is not legal for use in the European Union because of its reaction with carbon monoxide into toxic nickel tetracarbonyl.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] Upon failure, a catalytic converter can be recycled rather than being scrapped.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] The precious metals inside the converter – the platinum, palladium, and rhodium – are extracted.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] Catalytic converters require a temperature of 400 °C (750 °F) to operate effectively.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] Therefore, they are placed as close to the engine as possible, or one or more smaller catalytic converters (known as "pre-cats") are placed immediately after the exhaust manifold.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] The two-way catalytic converter is widely used on diesel engines to reduce hydrocarbon and carbon monoxide emissions.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] They were also used on gasoline engines in American and Canadian automobile markets until 1981.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] Because of their inability to control oxides of nitrogen, manufacturers briefly installed twin catalyst systems, with an NO*x* reducing, rhodium/platinum catalyst ahead of the air pump, which led to the development of the three-way catalytic converter.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] The two-way catalytic converter also continued to be used on certain, lower-cost cars in some markets such as Europe, where NO*x* emissions were not universally regulated until the introduction of the Euro 3 emissions standard in 2000.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] The three-way catalytic converters have the additional advantage of controlling the emission of nitric oxide (NO) and nitrogen dioxide (NO2) (both together abbreviated with NO*x* and not to be confused with nitrous oxide (N2O)).
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] NO*x* are precursors to acid rain and smog.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] The reduction and oxidation catalysts are typically contained in a common housing; however, in some instances, they may be housed separately.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] These three reactions occur most efficiently when the engine runs within a narrow band of air-fuel ratios near the stoichiometric point.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] Total conversion efficiency falls very rapidly when the engine is operated outside of this band.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] Slightly lean of stoichiometric, the exhaust gases from the engine contain excess oxygen, the production of NO*x* by the engine increases, and the efficiency of the catalyst at reducing NO*x* falls off rapidly.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] However, the conversion of HC and CO is very efficient due to the available oxygen, oxidizing to H2O and CO2.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] Slightly rich of stoichiometric, the production of CO and unburnt HC by the engine starts to increase dramatically, available oxygen decreases, and the efficiency of the catalyst for oxidizing CO and HC decreases significantly, especially as stored oxygen becomes depleted.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] However, the efficiency of the catalyst at reducing NO*x* is good, and the production of NO*x* by the engine decreases.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] To maintain catalyst efficiency, the air–fuel ratio must stay close to stoichiometric and not remain rich or lean for too long.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] Therefore, engines fitted with regulated 3-way catalytic converters have a closed-loop feedback carburetor or fuel injection engine control system to manage a continuous rich-lean balance required for effective NO*x* reduction and HC+CO oxidation.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] The control system allows the catalyst to release oxygen during slightly rich operating conditions, which oxidizes CO and HC under conditions that also favor the reduction of NOx.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] Before the stored oxygen is depleted, the control system shifts the air-fuel ratio to become slightly lean, improving HC and CO oxidation while storing additional oxygen in the catalyst material, at a small penalty in NO*x* reduction efficiency.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] Then the air–fuel mixture is brought back to slightly rich, at a small penalty in CO and HC oxidation efficiency, and the cycle repeats.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] Efficiency is improved when this oscillation around the stoichiometric point is small and carefully controlled.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] Closed-loop control under light to moderate load is accomplished by using one or more oxygen sensors in the exhaust system.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] When oxygen is detected by the sensor, the air-fuel ratio is lean of stoichiometric, and when oxygen is not detected, it is rich.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] The control system adjusts the amount of fuel being fed to the engine based on this signal to keep the air-fuel ratio near the stoichiometric point in order to maximize the catalyst conversion efficiency.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] The control algorithm is also affected by the time delay between the adjustment of the fuel flow rate and the sensing of the changed air–fuel ratio by the sensor, as well as the sigmoidal response of the oxygen sensors.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] Typical control systems are designed to rapidly sweep the air–fuel ratio such that it oscillates slightly around the stoichiometric point, staying near the optimal efficiency point while managing the levels of stored oxygen and unburnt HC.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] Closed-loop control is often suspended during high load/maximum power operation, when an increase in emissions is permitted and a rich mixture is commanded to increase power and prevent exhaust gas temperature from exceeding design limits.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] This presents a challenge for control system and catalyst design.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] During such operations, large amounts of unburnt HC are produced by the engine, well beyond the capacity of the catalyst to release oxygen.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] The surface of the catalyst quickly becomes saturated with HC.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] When returning to lower power output and leaner air-fuel ratios, the control system must prevent excessive oxygen from reaching the catalyst too quickly, as this will rapidly burn the HC in the already hot catalyst, potentially exceeding the design temperature limit of the catalyst.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] Excessive catalyst temperature can prematurely age the catalyst, reducing its efficiency before reaching its design lifetime.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] Excessive catalyst temperature can also be caused by cylinder misfire, which continuously flows unburnt HC combined with oxygen to the hot catalyst, burning in the catalyst and increasing its temperature.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] Unwanted reactions result in the formation of hydrogen sulfide and ammonia, which poison catalysts.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] Nickel or manganese is sometimes added to the washcoat to limit hydrogen-sulfide emissions.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] Sulfur-free or low-sulfur fuels eliminate or minimize problems with hydrogen sulfide.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] For compression-ignition (i.e., diesel) engines, the most commonly used catalytic converter is the *diesel oxidation catalyst* (DOC).
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] DOCs contain palladium or platinum supported on alumina.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] This catalyst converts particulate matter (PM), hydrocarbons, and carbon monoxide to carbon dioxide and water.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] These converters often operate at 90 percent efficiency, virtually eliminating diesel odor and helping reduce visible particulates.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] These catalysts are ineffective for NO*x*, so NO*x* emissions from diesel engines are controlled by exhaust gas recirculation (EGR).
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] In 2010, most light-duty diesel manufacturers in the U.S. added catalytic systems to their vehicles to meet federal emissions requirements.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] Two techniques have been developed for the catalytic reduction of NO*x* emissions under lean exhaust conditions, selective catalytic reduction (SCR) and the NO*x* adsorber.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] Instead of precious metal-containing NO*x* absorbers, most manufacturers selected base-metal SCR systems that use a reagent such as ammonia to reduce the NO*x* into nitrogen and water.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] Ammonia is supplied to the catalyst system by the injection of urea into the exhaust, which then undergoes thermal decomposition and hydrolysis into ammonia.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] The urea solution is also referred to as diesel exhaust fluid (DEF).
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] Diesel exhaust contains relatively high levels of particulate matter.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] Catalytic converters remove only 20–40% of PM so particulates are cleaned up by a soot trap or diesel particulate filter (DPF).
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] In the U.S., all on-road light, medium, and heavy-duty diesel-powered vehicles built after 1 January 2007, are subject to diesel particulate emission limits, and so are equipped with a 2-way catalytic converter and a diesel particulate filter.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] As long as the engine was manufactured before 1 January 2007, the vehicle is not required to have the DPF system.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] This led to an inventory runup by engine manufacturers in late 2006 so they could continue selling pre-DPF vehicles well into 2007.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] For lean-burn spark-ignition engines, an oxidation catalyst is used in the same manner as in a diesel engine.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] Emissions from lean burn spark ignition engines are very similar to emissions from a diesel compression ignition engine.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] Many vehicles have a close-coupled catalytic converter located near the engine's exhaust manifold.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] The converter heats up quickly, due to its exposure to the very hot exhaust gases, allowing it to reduce undesirable emissions during the engine warm-up period.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] This is achieved by burning off the excess hydrocarbons which result from the extra-rich mixture required for a cold start.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] When catalytic converters were first introduced, most vehicles used carburetors that provided a relatively rich air-fuel ratio.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] Oxygen (O2) levels in the exhaust stream were therefore generally insufficient for the catalytic reaction to occur efficiently.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] Most designs of the time therefore included secondary air injection, which injected air into the exhaust stream.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] This increased the available oxygen, allowing the catalyst to function as intended.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] Some three-way catalytic converter systems have air injection systems with the air injected between the first (NO*x* reduction) and second (HC and CO oxidation) stages of the converter.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] As in two-way converters, this injected air provides oxygen for the oxidation reactions.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] An upstream air injection point, ahead of the catalytic converter, is also sometimes present to provide additional oxygen only during the engine warm up period.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] This causes unburned fuel to ignite in the exhaust tract, thereby preventing it reaching the catalytic converter at all.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] This technique reduces the engine runtime needed for the catalytic converter to reach its "light-off" or operating temperature.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] Most newer vehicles have electronic fuel injection systems, and do not require air injection systems in their exhausts.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] Instead, they provide a precisely controlled air-fuel mixture that quickly and continually cycles between lean and rich combustion.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] Catalyst poisoning occurs when the catalytic converter is exposed to exhaust containing substances that coat the working surfaces, so that they cannot contact and react with the exhaust.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] The most notable contaminant is lead, so vehicles equipped with catalytic converters can run only on unleaded fuel.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] Other common catalyst poisons include sulfur, manganese (originating primarily from the gasoline additive MMT), and silicon, which can enter the exhaust stream if the engine has a leak that allows coolant into the combustion chamber.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] Phosphorus is another catalyst contaminant.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] Although phosphorus is no longer used in gasoline, it (and zinc, another low-level catalyst contaminant) was widely used in engine oil antiwear additives such as zinc dithiophosphate (ZDDP).
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] Beginning in 2004, a limit of phosphorus concentration in engine oils was adopted in the API SM and ILSAC GF-4 specifications.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] Depending on the contaminant, catalyst poisoning can sometimes be reversed by running the engine under a very heavy load for an extended period of time.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] The increased exhaust temperature can sometimes vaporize or sublimate the contaminant, removing it from the catalytic surface.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] However, removal of lead deposits in this manner is usually not possible because of lead's high boiling point.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] Oil and coolant leaks, perhaps caused by a head gasket leak, can also cause high unburned hydrocarbons.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] Emissions regulations vary considerably from jurisdiction to jurisdiction.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] Most automobile spark-ignition engines in North America have been fitted with catalytic converters since 1975, and the technology used in non-automotive applications is generally based on automotive technology.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] In many jurisdictions, it is illegal to remove or disable a catalytic converter for any reason other than its direct and immediate replacement.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] Nevertheless, some vehicle owners remove or "gut" the catalytic converter on their vehicle.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] In such cases, the converter may be replaced by a welded-in section of ordinary pipe or a flanged "test pipe", ostensibly meant to check if the converter is clogged by comparing how the engine runs with and without the converter.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] This facilitates temporary reinstallation of the converter in order to pass an emission test.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] Vehicles without functioning catalytic converters generally fail emission inspections.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] The automotive aftermarket supplies high-flow converters for vehicles with upgraded engines, or whose owners prefer an exhaust system with larger-than-stock capacity.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] Catalytic converters have been mandatory on all new gasoline cars sold in the European Union and the United Kingdom since 1 January 1993 in order to comply with the Euro 1 emission standards.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] Faulty catalytic converters as well as undamaged early types of converters can restrict the flow of exhaust, which negatively affects vehicle performance and fuel economy.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] Modern catalytic converters do not significantly restrict exhaust flow.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] A 2006 test on a 1999 Honda Civic, for example, showed that removing the stock catalytic converter netted only a 3% increase in maximum horsepower; a new metallic core converter only cost the car 1% horsepower, compared to no converter.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] Carburetors on pre-1981 vehicles without feedback fuel-air mixture control could easily provide too much fuel to the engine, which could cause the catalytic converter to overheat and potentially ignite flammable materials under the car.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] Vehicles fitted with catalytic converters emit most of their total pollution during the first five minutes of engine operation; that is, before the catalytic converter has warmed up sufficiently to be fully effective.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] In the early 2000s it became common to place the catalyst converter right next to the exhaust manifold, close to the engine, for much quicker warm-up.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] In 1995, Alpina introduced an electrically heated catalyst.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] Called "E-KAT", it was used in Alpina's B12 5,7 E-KAT based on the BMW 750i.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] Heating coils inside the catalytic converter assemblies are electrified just after the engine is started, bringing the catalyst up to operating temperature very quickly to qualify the vehicle for low emission vehicle (LEV) designation.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] BMW later introduced the same heated catalyst, developed jointly by Emitec, Alpina, and BMW, in its 750i in 1999.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] Some vehicles contain a pre-cat, a small catalytic converter upstream of the main catalytic converter which heats up faster on vehicle start up, reducing the emissions associated with cold starts.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] A pre-cat is most commonly used by an auto manufacturer when trying to attain the Ultra Low Emissions Vehicle (ULEV) rating, such as on the Toyota MR2 Roadster.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] Catalytic converters have proven to be reliable and effective in reducing noxious tailpipe emissions.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] Because of the external location and the use of valuable precious metals including platinum, palladium and rhodium, catalytic converters are a target for thieves.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] The problem is especially common among late-model pickup trucks and truck-based SUVs, because of their high ground clearance and easily removed bolt-on catalytic converters.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] Welded-on converters are also at risk of theft, as they can be easily cut off.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] Pipecutters are often used to quietly remove the converter but other tools such as a portable reciprocating saw can damage other components of the car, such as the oxygen sensor, wiring or fuel lines, with potentially dangerous consequences.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] In 2023, bipartisan legislation to combat catalytic converter theft was introduced in the U.S.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] The Preventing Auto Recycling Thefts Act (PART Act) would mandate catalytic converters in new vehicles to come with traceable identification numbers.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] Additionally, the legislation would make catalytic converter theft a federal criminal offense.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] Rising metal prices in the U.S. during the 2000s commodities boom led to a significant increase in converter theft.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] A catalytic converter can cost more than $1,000 to replace, more if the vehicle is damaged during the theft.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] Apart from damaging other systems of the vehicle, theft can also cause death and injury to thieves.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] Thefts of catalytic converters rose over tenfold in the United States from the late 2010s to early 2020s, driven presumably by the rise in the price of precious metals contained within the converters.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] Study findings reveal an average price elasticity of 1.98, which means that a 10 percent increase in the price of metal leads to an approximate 20 percent increase in thefts.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] According to the National Insurance Crime Bureau, there were 1,298 reported cases of catalytic converter theft in 2018, which increased to 14,433 in 2020.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] In 2022, it was reported that the number of catalytic converter thefts in the United States sharply rose to 153,000 total thefts for the year.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] From 2019 to 2020, thieves in the United Kingdom were targeting older-model hybrid cars (such as Toyota's hybrids) which have more precious metals than newer vehicles—sometimes worth more than the value of the car—leading to scarcity and long delays in replacing them.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] In 2021 a trend emerged in the Democratic Republic of the Congo where catalytic converters were alleged to be stolen for use in illicit street drug production.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] The drug, a powder known as "bombé," was said to be a mixture of powdered pills/vitamins and pulverized honeycomb structures of catalytic converters.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] In 2023, however, a study of various samples of the drug concluded that its alleged origin from catalytic exhausts was found to be unsubstantiated.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] Various jurisdictions now require on-board diagnostics to monitor the function and condition of the emissions-control system, including the catalytic converter.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] Vehicles equipped with OBD-II diagnostic systems are designed to alert the driver to a misfire condition by means of illuminating the "check engine" light on the dashboard, or flashing it if the current misfire conditions are severe enough to potentially damage the catalytic converter.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] On-board diagnostic systems take several forms.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] Temperature sensors are used for two purposes.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] The first is as a warning system, typically on two-way catalytic converters such as those used on LPG forklifts.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] The function of the sensor is to warn of catalytic converter temperature above the safe limit of 750 °C (1,380 °F).
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] Modern catalytic-converter designs are not as susceptible to temperature damage and can withstand sustained temperatures of 900 °C (1,650 °F).
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] Temperature sensors are also used to monitor catalyst functioning: usually two sensors will be fitted, with one before the catalyst and one after to monitor the temperature rise over the catalytic-converter core.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] The oxygen sensor is the basis of the closed-loop control system on a spark-ignited rich-burn engine; however, it is also used for diagnostics.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] In vehicles with OBD II, a second oxygen sensor is fitted after the catalytic converter to monitor the O2 levels.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] The O2 levels are monitored to see the efficiency of the burn process.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] The on-board computer makes comparisons between the readings of the two sensors.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] The readings are taken by voltage measurements.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] If both sensors show the same output or the rear O2 is "switching", the computer recognizes that the catalytic converter either is not functioning or has been removed, and will operate a malfunction indicator lamp and affect engine performance.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] Simple "oxygen sensor simulators" have been developed to circumvent this problem by simulating the change across the catalytic converter with plans and pre-assembled devices available on the Internet.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] Although these are not legal for on-road use, they have been used with mixed results.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] Similar devices apply an offset to the sensor signals, allowing the engine to run a more fuel-economical lean burn that may, however, damage the engine or the catalytic converter.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] NO*x* sensors are extremely expensive and are in general used only when a compression-ignition engine is fitted with a selective catalytic-reduction (SCR) converter, or a NO*x* absorber in a feedback system.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] When fitted to an SCR system, there may be one or two sensors.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] When one sensor is fitted it will be pre-catalyst; when two are fitted, the second one will be post-catalyst.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/catalytic-converter] They are used for the same reasons and in the same manner as an oxygen sensor; the only difference is the substance being monitored.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/chemisorption] In contrast with chemisorption is physisorption, which leaves the chemical species of the adsorbate and surface intact.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/chemisorption] It is conventionally accepted that the energetic threshold separating the binding energy of "physisorption" from that of "chemisorption" is about 0.5 eV per adsorbed species.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/chemisorption] Due to specificity, the nature of chemisorption can greatly differ, depending on the chemical identity and the surface structural properties.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/chemisorption] The bond between the adsorbate and adsorbent in chemisorption is either ionic or covalent.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/chemisorption] An important example of chemisorption is in heterogeneous catalysis which involves molecules reacting with each other via the formation of chemisorbed intermediates.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/chemisorption] After the chemisorbed species combine (by forming bonds with each other) the product desorbs from the surface.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/chemisorption] Self-assembled monolayers (SAMs) are formed by chemisorbing reactive reagents with metal surfaces.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/chemisorption] A famous example involves thiols (R-SH) adsorbing onto the surface of gold.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/chemisorption] This process forms strong Au-SR bonds and releases H2.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/chemisorption] The densely packed SR groups protect the surface.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/chemisorption] As an instance of adsorption, chemisorption follows the adsorption process.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/chemisorption] The first stage is for the adsorbate particle to come into contact with the surface.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/chemisorption] The particle needs to be trapped onto the surface by not possessing enough energy to leave the gas-surface potential well.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/chemisorption] If it elastically collides with the surface, then it would return to the bulk gas.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/chemisorption] If it loses enough momentum through an inelastic collision, then it "sticks" onto the surface, forming a precursor state bonded to the surface by weak forces, similar to physisorption.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/chemisorption] The particle diffuses on the surface until it finds a deep chemisorption potential well.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/chemisorption] Then it reacts with the surface or simply desorbs after enough energy and time.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/chemisorption] The reaction with the surface is dependent on the chemical species involved.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/chemisorption] General thermodynamics states that for spontaneous reactions at constant temperature and pressure, the change in free energy should be negative.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/chemisorption] Since a free particle is restrained to a surface, and unless the surface atom is highly mobile, entropy is lowered.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/chemisorption] This means that the enthalpy term must be negative, implying an exothermic reaction.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/chemisorption] Physisorption is given as a Lennard-Jones potential and chemisorption is given as a Morse potential.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/chemisorption] There exists a point of crossover between the physisorption and chemisorption, meaning a point of transfer.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/chemisorption] It can occur above or below the zero-energy line (with a difference in the Morse potential, a), representing an activation energy requirement or lack of.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/chemisorption] Most simple gases on clean metal surfaces lack the activation energy requirement.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/chemisorption] For experimental setups of chemisorption, the amount of adsorption of a particular system is quantified by a sticking probability value.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/chemisorption] However, chemisorption is very difficult to theorize.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/chemisorption] A multidimensional potential energy surface (PES) derived from effective medium theory is used to describe the effect of the surface on absorption, but only certain parts of it are used depending on what is to be studied.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/chemisorption] where $E_{el}$ is the energy eigenvalue of the Schrödinger equation for the electronic degrees of freedom and $V_{ion-ion}$ is the ion interactions.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/chemisorption] This expression is without translational energy, rotational energy, vibrational excitations, and other such considerations.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/chemisorption] There exist several models to describe surface reactions: the Langmuir–Hinshelwood mechanism in which both reacting species are adsorbed, and the Eley–Rideal mechanism in which one is adsorbed and the other reacts with it.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/chemisorption] Compared to physisorption where adsorbates are simply sitting on the surface, the adsorbates can change the surface, along with its structure.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/chemisorption] The structure can go through relaxation, where the first few layers change interplanar distances without changing the surface structure, or reconstruction where the surface structure is changed.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/chemisorption] A direct transition from physisorption to chemisorption has been observed by attaching a CO molecule to the tip of an atomic force microscope and measuring its interaction with a single iron atom.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/chemisorption] For example, oxygen can form very strong bonds (~4 eV) with metals, such as Cu(110).
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/chemisorption] This comes with the breaking apart of surface bonds in forming surface-adsorbate bonds.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/chemisorption] A large restructuring occurs by missing row.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/chemisorption] A particular brand of gas-surface chemisorption is the dissociation of diatomic gas molecules, such as hydrogen, oxygen, and nitrogen.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/chemisorption] One model used to describe the process is precursor-mediation.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/chemisorption] The absorbed molecule is adsorbed onto a surface into a precursor state.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/chemisorption] The molecule then diffuses across the surface to the chemisorption sites.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/chemisorption] They break the molecular bond in favor of new bonds to the surface.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/chemisorption] The energy to overcome the activation potential of dissociation usually comes from translational energy and vibrational energy.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/chemisorption] An example is the hydrogen and copper system, one that has been studied many times over.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/chemisorption] It has a large activation energy of 0.35 – 0.85 eV.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/chemisorption] The vibrational excitation of the hydrogen molecule promotes dissociation on low index surfaces of copper.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/heterogeneous-catalysis] Heterogeneous catalysis typically involves solid phase catalysts and gas phase reactants.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/heterogeneous-catalysis] In this case, there is a cycle of molecular adsorption, reaction, and desorption occurring at the catalyst surface.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/heterogeneous-catalysis] Thermodynamics, mass transfer, and heat transfer influence the rate (kinetics) of reaction.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/heterogeneous-catalysis] Heterogeneous catalysis is very important because it enables faster, large-scale production and the selective product formation.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/heterogeneous-catalysis] Approximately 35% of the world's GDP is influenced by catalysis.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/heterogeneous-catalysis] The production of 90% of chemicals (by volume) is assisted by solid catalysts.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/heterogeneous-catalysis] The chemical and energy industries rely heavily on heterogeneous catalysis.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/heterogeneous-catalysis] For example, the Haber–Bosch process uses metal-based catalysts in the synthesis of ammonia, an important component in fertilizer; 144 million tons of ammonia were produced in 2016.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/heterogeneous-catalysis] Adsorption is an essential step in heterogeneous catalysis.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/heterogeneous-catalysis] Adsorption is the process by which a gas (or solution) phase molecule (the adsorbate) binds to solid (or liquid) surface atoms (the adsorbent).
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/heterogeneous-catalysis] The reverse of adsorption is desorption, the adsorbate splitting from adsorbent.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/heterogeneous-catalysis] In a reaction facilitated by heterogeneous catalysis, the catalyst is the adsorbent and the reactants are the adsorbate.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/heterogeneous-catalysis] Two types of adsorption are recognized: physisorption, weakly bound adsorption, and chemisorption, strongly bound adsorption.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/heterogeneous-catalysis] Many processes in heterogeneous catalysis lie between the two extremes.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/heterogeneous-catalysis] The Lennard-Jones model provides a basic framework for predicting molecular interactions as a function of atomic separation.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/heterogeneous-catalysis] In physisorption, a molecule becomes attracted to the surface atoms via van der Waals forces.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/heterogeneous-catalysis] These include dipole-dipole interactions, induced dipole interactions, and London dispersion forces.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/heterogeneous-catalysis] Note that no chemical bonds are formed between adsorbate and adsorbent, and their electronic states remain relatively unperturbed.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/heterogeneous-catalysis] Typical energies for physisorption are from 3 to 10 kcal/mol.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/heterogeneous-catalysis] In heterogeneous catalysis, when a reactant molecule physisorbs to a catalyst, it is commonly said to be in a precursor state, an intermediate energy state before chemisorption, a more strongly bound adsorption.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/heterogeneous-catalysis] From the precursor state, a molecule can either undergo chemisorption, desorption, or migration across the surface.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/heterogeneous-catalysis] The nature of the precursor state can influence the reaction kinetics.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/heterogeneous-catalysis] When a molecule approaches close enough to surface atoms such that their electron clouds overlap, chemisorption can occur.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/heterogeneous-catalysis] In chemisorption, the adsorbate and adsorbent share electrons signifying the formation of chemical bonds.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/heterogeneous-catalysis] Typical energies for chemisorption range from 20 to 100 kcal/mol.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/heterogeneous-catalysis] Most metal surface reactions occur by chain propagation in which catalytic intermediates are cyclically produced and consumed.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/heterogeneous-catalysis] Two main mechanisms for surface reactions can be described for A + B → C.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/heterogeneous-catalysis] Most heterogeneously catalyzed reactions are described by the Langmuir–Hinshelwood model.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/heterogeneous-catalysis] In heterogeneous catalysis, reactants diffuse from the bulk fluid phase to adsorb to the catalyst surface.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/heterogeneous-catalysis] The adsorption site is not always an active catalyst site, so reactant molecules must migrate across the surface to an active site.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/heterogeneous-catalysis] At the active site, reactant molecules will react to form product molecule(s) by following a more energetically facile path through catalytic intermediates (see figure to the right).
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/heterogeneous-catalysis] The product molecules then desorb from the surface and diffuse away.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/heterogeneous-catalysis] The catalyst itself remains intact and free to mediate further reactions.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/heterogeneous-catalysis] Transport phenomena such as heat and mass transfer, also play a role in the observed reaction rate.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/heterogeneous-catalysis] Catalysts are not active towards reactants across their entire surface; only specific locations possess catalytic activity, called **active sites**.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/heterogeneous-catalysis] The surface area of a solid catalyst has a strong influence on the number of available active sites.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/heterogeneous-catalysis] In industrial practice, solid catalysts are often porous to maximize surface area, commonly achieving 50–400 m2/g.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/heterogeneous-catalysis] Some mesoporous silicates, such as the MCM-41, have surface areas greater than 1000 m2/g.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/heterogeneous-catalysis] Porous materials are cost effective due to their high surface area-to-mass ratio and enhanced catalytic activity.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/heterogeneous-catalysis] In many cases, a solid catalyst is dispersed on a supporting material to increase surface area (spread the number of active sites) and provide stability.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/heterogeneous-catalysis] Usually catalyst supports are inert, high melting point materials, but they can also be catalytic themselves.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/heterogeneous-catalysis] Most catalyst supports are porous (frequently carbon, silica, zeolite, or alumina-based) and chosen for their high surface area-to-mass ratio.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/heterogeneous-catalysis] For a given reaction, porous supports must be selected such that reactants and products can enter and exit the material.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/heterogeneous-catalysis] Often, substances are intentionally added to the reaction feed or on the catalyst to influence catalytic activity, selectivity, and/or stability.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/heterogeneous-catalysis] For example, alumina (Al2O3) is added during ammonia synthesis to providing greater stability by slowing sintering processes on the Fe-catalyst.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/heterogeneous-catalysis] Sabatier principle can be considered one of the cornerstones of modern theory of catalysis.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/heterogeneous-catalysis] Sabatier principle states that the surface-adsorbates interaction has to be an optimal amount: not too weak to be inert toward the reactants and not too strong to poison the surface and avoid desorption of the products.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/heterogeneous-catalysis] The statement that the surface-adsorbate interaction has to be an optimum, is a qualitative one.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/heterogeneous-catalysis] Usually the number of adsorbates and transition states associated with a chemical reaction is a large number, thus the optimum has to be found in a many-dimensional space.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/heterogeneous-catalysis] Catalyst design in such a many-dimensional space is not a computationally viable task.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/heterogeneous-catalysis] Additionally, such optimization process would be far from intuitive.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/heterogeneous-catalysis] Scaling relations are used to decrease the dimensionality of the space of catalyst design.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/heterogeneous-catalysis] Such relations are correlations among adsorbates binding energies (or among adsorbate binding energies and transition states also known as BEP relations) that are "similar enough" e.g., OH versus OOH scaling.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/heterogeneous-catalysis] Applying scaling relations to the catalyst design problems greatly reduces the space dimensionality (sometimes to as small as 1 or 2).
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/heterogeneous-catalysis] One can also use micro-kinetic modeling based on such scaling relations to take into account the kinetics associated with adsorption, reaction and desorption of molecules under specific pressure or temperature conditions.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/heterogeneous-catalysis] Such modeling then leads to well-known volcano-plots at which the optimum qualitatively described by the Sabatier principle is referred to as the "top of the volcano".
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/heterogeneous-catalysis] Scaling relations can be used not only to connect the energetics of radical surface-adsorbed groups (e.g., O*,OH*), but also to connect the energetics of closed-shell molecules among each other or to the counterpart radical adsorbates.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/heterogeneous-catalysis] A recent challenge for researchers in catalytic sciences is to "break" the scaling relations.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/heterogeneous-catalysis] The correlations which are manifested in the scaling relations confine the catalyst design space, preventing one from reaching the "top of the volcano".
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/heterogeneous-catalysis] In addition to studying catalytic reactivity, scaling relations can be used to study and screen materials for selectivity toward a special product.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/heterogeneous-catalysis] There are special combination of binding energies that favor specific products over the others.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/heterogeneous-catalysis] Catalyst deactivation is defined as a loss in catalytic activity and/or selectivity over time.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/heterogeneous-catalysis] Substances that decrease the reaction rate are called **poisons**.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/heterogeneous-catalysis] Poisons chemisorb to the catalyst surface and reduce the number of available active sites for reactant molecules to bind to.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/heterogeneous-catalysis] Common poisons include Group V, VI, and VII elements (e.g.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/heterogeneous-catalysis] As, Pb), and adsorbing species with multiple bonds (e.g.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/heterogeneous-catalysis] For example, sulfur disrupts the production of methanol by poisoning the Cu/ZnO catalyst.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/heterogeneous-catalysis] Substances that increase reaction rate are called **promoters**.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/heterogeneous-catalysis] For example, the presence of alkali metals in ammonia synthesis increases the rate of N2 dissociation.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/heterogeneous-catalysis] The presence of poisons and promoters can alter the activation energy of the rate-limiting step and affect a catalyst's selectivity for the formation of certain products.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/heterogeneous-catalysis] Depending on the amount, a substance can be favorable or unfavorable for a chemical process.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/heterogeneous-catalysis] For example, in the production of ethylene, a small amount of chemisorbed chlorine will act as a promoter by improving Ag-catalyst selectivity towards ethylene over CO2, while too much chlorine will act as a poison.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/heterogeneous-catalysis] In industry, catalyst deactivation costs billions every year due to process shutdown and catalyst replacement.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/heterogeneous-catalysis] In industry, many design variables must be considered including reactor and catalyst design across multiple scales ranging from the subnanometer to tens of meters.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/heterogeneous-catalysis] The conventional heterogeneous catalysis reactors include batch, continuous, and fluidized-bed reactors, while more recent setups include fixed-bed, microchannel, and multi-functional reactors.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/heterogeneous-catalysis] Other variables to consider are reactor dimensions, surface area, catalyst type, catalyst support, as well as reactor operating conditions such as temperature, pressure, and reactant concentrations.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/heterogeneous-catalysis] Some large-scale industrial processes incorporating heterogeneous catalysts are listed below.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/heterogeneous-catalysis] Although the majority of heterogeneous catalysts are solids, there are a few variations which are of practical value.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/heterogeneous-catalysis] For two immiscible solutions (liquids), one carries the catalyst while the other carries the reactant.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/heterogeneous-catalysis] This set up is the basis of biphasic catalysis as implemented in the industrial production of butyraldehyde by the hydroformylation of propylene.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] The term was originally coined in 1756 by Swedish mineralogist Axel Fredrik Cronstedt, who observed that rapidly heating a material, believed to have been stilbite, produced large amounts of steam from water that had been adsorbed by the material.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] Based on this, he called the material *zeolith* (changed later to *zeolite* in English, to fit the naming scheme for minerals in *-ite*) from the Greek ζέω (zéō), meaning "to boil" and λίθος (líthos), meaning "stone".
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] The first synthetic structure was reported by Richard Barrer in 1948.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] Industrially important zeolites are produced synthetically.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] Over 200 synthetic zeolites have been reported.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] Synthetic zeolites hold some key advantages over their natural analogs.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] The synthetic materials are manufactured in a uniform, phase-pure state.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] It is also possible to produce zeolite structures that do not appear in nature.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] The principal raw materials used to manufacture zeolites are silica and alumina, which are among the most abundant mineral components on earth.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] Zeolites occur naturally, but are also produced industrially on a large scale.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] As of December 2018, 253 unique zeolite frameworks have been identified, and over 40 naturally occurring zeolite frameworks are known.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] Every new zeolite structure that is obtained is examined by the International Zeolite Association Structure Commission (IZA-SC) and receives a three-letter designation.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] Zeolites are white solids with ordinary handling properties, like many routine aluminosilicate minerals, e.g. feldspar.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] They have the general formula (MAlO2)(SiO2)x(H2O)y where M+ is usually H+ and Na+.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] The Si/Al ratio is variable, which provides a means to tune the properties.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] Zeolites with a Si/Al ratios higher than about 3 are classified as **high-silica zeolites**, which tend to be more hydrophobic.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] The H+ and Na+ can be replaced by diverse cations, because zeolites have ion exchange properties.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] The nature of the cations influences the porosity of zeolites.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] Zeolites have microporous structures with a typical diameter of 0.3–0.8 nm.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] Like most aluminosilicates, the framework is formed by linking of aluminium and silicon atoms by oxides.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] This linking leads to a 3-dimensional network of Si-O-Al, Si-O-Si, and Al-O-Al linkages.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] The aluminium centers are negatively charged, which requires an accompanying cation.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] These cations are hydrated during the formation of the materials.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] The hydrated cations interrupt the otherwise dense network of Si-O-Al, Si-O-Si, and Al-O-Al linkage, leading to regular water-filled cavities.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] Because of the porosity of the zeolite, the water can exit the material through channels.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] Because of the rigidity of the zeolite framework, the loss of water does not result in collapse of the cavities and channels.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] Their ability to generate voids within a rigid solid underpins the use of zeolites as catalysts and molecular sieves.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] They possess high physical and chemical stability due to the covalent bonding within their framework.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] Some are hydrophobic and thus are suited for adsorption of hydrophobic molecules such as hydrocarbons.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] In addition to that, high-silica zeolites are H+ exchangeable, unlike natural zeolites, and are used as solid acid catalysts.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] The high silica zeolites especially are sufficiently acidic to protonate hydrocarbons.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] These are used for fluid catalytic cracking in petrochemical industry.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] Cracking catalysts become poisoned by carbonaceous residues.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] These residues can be combusted without major damage to the host zeolite, a further testament to their robustness.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] For some applications, such regenerated zeolites are called equilibrium catalysts.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] The structures of hundreds of zeolites have been determined.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] For each structure, the International Zeolite Association (IZA) gives a three-letter code called framework type code (FTC).
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] For example, the major molecular sieves, 3A, 4A and 5A, are all LTA (Linde Type A).
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] Most commercially available natural zeolites are of the MOR, HEU or ANA-types.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] An example of the notation of the ring structure of zeolite and other silicate materials is shown in the upper right figure.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] The middle figure shows a common notation using structural formula.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] The left figure emphasizes the SiO4 tetrahedral structure.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] Connecting oxygen atoms together creates a four-membered ring of oxygen (blue bold line).
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] In fact, such a ring substructure is called **four membered ring** or simply **four-ring**.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] The figure on the right shows a 4-ring with Si atoms connected to each other, which is the most common way to express the topology of the framework.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] The figure on the right compares the typical framework structures of LTA (left) and FAU (right).
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] Both zeolites share the truncated octahedral structure (sodalite cage) (purple line).
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] However, the way they are connected (yellow line) is different: in LTA, the four-membered rings of the cage are connected to each other to form a skeleton, while in FAU, the six-membered rings are connected to each other.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] As a result, the pore entrance of LTA is an 8-ring (0.41 nm) and belongs to the **small pore zeolite**, while the pore entrance of FAU is a 12-ring (0.74 nm) and belongs to the **large pore zeolite**, respectively.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] Materials with a 10-ring are called **medium pore zeolites**, a typical example being ZSM-5 (MFI).
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] Although more than 200 types of zeolites are known, only about 100 types of aluminosilicate are available.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] In addition, there are only a few types that can be synthesized in industrially feasible way and have sufficient thermal stability to meet the requirements for industrial use.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] In particular, the FAU (faujasite, USY), *BEA (beta), MOR (high-silica mordenite), MFI (ZSM-5), and FER (high-silica ferrierite) types are called the **big five** of high silica zeolites, and industrial production methods have been established.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] The scope of zeolites is greatly expanded because Si and Al in zeolites can be at least partially replaced with other atoms without major changes in the overall framework, i.e., isomorphous replacement.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] Germanium, iron, gallium, boron, zinc, tin, and titanium have been investigated.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] Other heteroatoms have been claimed, including titanium, and zinc Al atoms in zeolites can be also structurally replaced with boron and gallium.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] The silicoaluminophosphate type (AlPO molecular sieve), in which Si is isomorphous with Al and P and Al is isomorphous with Si, and the gallogermanate and others are known.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] The term molecular sieve refers to a particular property of these materials, i.e., the ability to selectively sort molecules based primarily on a size exclusion process.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] This is due to a very regular pore structure of molecular dimensions.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] The maximum size of the molecular or ionic species that can enter the pores of a zeolite is controlled by the dimensions of the channels.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] These are conventionally defined by the ring size of the aperture, where, for example, the term "eight-ring" refers to a closed-loop that is built from eight tetrahedrally coordinated silicon (or aluminium) atoms and eight oxygen atoms.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] These rings are not always perfectly symmetrical due to a variety of causes, including strain induced by the bonding between units that are needed to produce the overall structure or coordination of some of the oxygen atoms of the rings to cations within the structure.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] Therefore, the pores in many zeolites are not cylindrical.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] Some of the more common mineral zeolites are analcime, chabazite, clinoptilolite, heulandite, natrolite, phillipsite, and stilbite.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] An example of the mineral formula of a zeolite is: Na2Al2Si3O10·2H2O, the formula for natrolite.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] Zeolites transform to other minerals under weathering, hydrothermal alteration or metamorphic conditions.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] As of 2016, the world's annual production of natural zeolite approximates 3 million tonnes.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] The ready availability of zeolite-rich rock at low cost and the shortage of competing minerals and rocks are probably the most important factors for its large-scale use.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] According to the United States Geological Survey, it is likely that a significant percentage of the material sold as zeolites in some countries is ground or sawn volcanic tuff that contains only a small amount of zeolites.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] These materials are used for construction, e.g. dimension stone (as an altered volcanic tuff), lightweight aggregate, pozzolanic cement, and soil conditioners.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] Typical procedures entail heating aqueous solutions of alumina and silica with sodium hydroxide.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] Equivalent reagents include sodium aluminate and sodium silicate.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] Further variations include the use of structure directing agents (SDA) such as quaternary ammonium cations.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] Zeolite synthesis involves sol-gel-like processes.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] The product properties depend on reaction mixture composition, pH of the system, operating temperature, pre-reaction 'seeding' time, reaction time as well as the templates used.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] In the sol-gel process, other elements (metals, metal oxides) can be incorporated.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] Zeolites are widely used as catalysts and sorbents.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] In chemistry, zeolites are used as membranes to separate molecules (only molecules of certain sizes and shapes can pass through), and as traps for molecules so they can be analyzed.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] Research into and development of the many biochemical and biomedical applications of zeolites, particularly the naturally occurring species heulandite, clinoptilolite, and chabazite has been ongoing.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] Zeolites are widely used as ion-exchange beds in domestic and commercial water purification, softening, and other applications.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] Evidence for the oldest known zeolite water purification filtration system occurs in the undisturbed sediments of the Corriental reservoir at the Maya city of Tikal, in northern Guatemala.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] Earlier, polyphosphates were used to soften hard water.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] The polyphosphates form a complex with metal ions like Ca2+ and Mg2+ to bind them so that they can not interfere in cleaning process.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] However, when this phosphate rich water goes in main stream water, it results in eutrophication of water bodies and hence use of polyphosphate was replaced with use of a synthetic zeolite.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] The largest single use for zeolite is the global laundry detergent market.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] Zeolites are used in laundry detergent as water softeners, removing Ca2+ and Mg2+ ions which would otherwise precipitate from the solution.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] The ions are retained by the zeolites which release Na+ ions into the solution, allowing the laundry detergent to be effective in areas with hard water.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] Synthetic zeolites, like other mesoporous materials (e.g., MCM-41), are widely used as catalysts in the petrochemical industry, such as in fluid catalytic cracking and hydrocracking.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] Zeolites confine molecules into small spaces, which causes changes in their structure and reactivity.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] The acidic forms of zeolites are often powerful solid-state solid acids, facilitating a host of acid-catalyzed reactions, such as isomerization, alkylation, and cracking.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] Catalytic cracking uses a reactor and a regenerator.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] Feed is injected onto a hot, fluidized catalyst where large gasoil molecules are broken into smaller gasoline molecules and olefins.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] The vapor-phase products are separated from the catalyst and distilled into various products.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] The catalyst is circulated to a regenerator, where the air is used to burn coke off the surface of the catalyst that was formed as a byproduct in the cracking process.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] The hot, regenerated catalyst is then circulated back to the reactor to complete its cycle.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] Zeolites have been used in advanced nuclear reprocessing methods, where their micro-porous ability to capture some ions while allowing others to pass freely allows many fission products to be efficiently removed from the waste and permanently trapped.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] Equally important are the mineral properties of zeolites.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] Their alumino-silicate construction is extremely durable and resistant to radiation, even in porous form.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] Additionally, once they are loaded with trapped fission products, the zeolite-waste combination can be hot-pressed into an extremely durable ceramic form, closing the pores and trapping the waste in a solid stone block.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] This is a waste form factor that greatly reduces its hazard, compared to conventional reprocessing systems.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] Zeolites are also used in the management of leaks of radioactive materials.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] For example, in the aftermath of the Fukushima Daiichi nuclear disaster, sandbags of zeolite were dropped into the seawater near the power plant to adsorb the radioactive cesium-137 that was present in high levels.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] Zeolites have the potential of providing precise and specific separation of gases, including the removal of H2O, CO2, and SO2 from low-grade natural gas streams.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] Other separations include noble gases, N2, O2, freon, and formaldehyde.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] On-board oxygen generating systems (OBOGS) and oxygen concentrators use zeolites in conjunction with pressure swing adsorption to remove nitrogen from compressed air to supply oxygen for aircrews at high altitudes, as well as home and portable oxygen supplies.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] Zeolite-based oxygen concentrator systems are widely used to produce medical-grade oxygen.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] The zeolite is used as a molecular sieve to create purified oxygen from air using its ability to trap impurities, in a process involving the adsorption of nitrogen, leaving highly purified oxygen and up to 5% argon.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] Zeolites are also used as a molecular sieve in cryosorption style vacuum pumps.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] Zeolites can be used to thermochemically store solar heat harvested from solar thermal collectors as first demonstrated by Guerra in 1978 and for adsorption refrigeration, as first demonstrated by Tchernev in 1974.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] In these applications, their high heat of adsorption and ability to hydrate and dehydrate while maintaining structural stability is exploited.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] This hygroscopic property coupled with an inherent exothermic (energy releasing) reaction when transitioning from a dehydrated form to a hydrated form make natural zeolites useful in harvesting waste heat and solar heat energy.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] Synthetic zeolites are used as an additive in the production process of warm mix asphalt concrete.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] The development of this application started in Germany in the 1990s.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] They help by decreasing the temperature level during manufacture and laying of asphalt concrete, resulting in lower consumption of fossil fuels, thus releasing less carbon dioxide, aerosols, and vapors.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] The use of synthetic zeolites in hot mixed asphalt leads to easier compaction and, to a certain degree, allows cold weather paving and longer hauls.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] When added to Portland cement as a pozzolan, they can reduce chloride permeability and improve workability.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] They reduce weight and help moderate water content while allowing for slower drying, which improves break strength.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] When added to lime mortars and lime-metakaolin mortars, synthetic zeolite pellets can act simultaneously as a pozzolanic material and a water reservoir.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] Zeolites have been studied as supplementary materials in cementitious mortars to improve mechanical performance and sustainability.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] Industrial waste-based zeolites, such as NaP-type and LTA-type zeolites derived from hazardous aluminum waste, can partially replace cement in mortars (5–15% substitution).
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] The LTA-type zeolite, with smaller particle size, acts as a filler and nucleation site for cement hydrates, accelerating hydration and increasing early compressive strength.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] NaP-type zeolite, with higher silica content, promotes pozzolanic reactions that enhance long-term compressive strength of the mortars.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] Non-clumping cat litter is often made of zeolite (or diatomite).
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] Zeolites are filter additives in aquaria, where they can be used to adsorb ammonia and other nitrogenous compounds.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] Due to the high affinity of some zeolites for calcium, they may be less effective in hard water and may deplete calcium.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] Zeolite filtration is also used in some marine aquaria to keep nutrient concentrations low for the benefit of corals adapted to nutrient-depleted waters.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] The original formulation of QuikClot brand hemostatic agent, which is used to stop severe bleeding, contained zeolite granules.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] When in contact with blood, the granules would rapidly absorb water from the blood plasma, creating an exothermic reaction which generated heat.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] The absorption of water would also concentrate clotting factors present within the blood, causing the clot formation process to occur much faster than under normal circumstances, as shown in vitro.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] The 2022 formulation of QuikClot uses a nonwoven material impregnated with kaolin, an inorganic mineral activating Factor XII, in turn accelerating natural clotting.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] Unlike the original zeolite formulation, kaolin does not exhibit any thermogenic properties.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] The microporous structure of the zeolites put into ground stabilizes water release and pH.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] In agriculture, clinoptilolite (a naturally occurring zeolite) is used as a soil treatment.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] It provides a source of slowly released potassium.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] If previously loaded with ammonium, the zeolite can serve a similar function in the slow release of nitrogen.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] Zeolites can also act as water moderators, in which they will absorb up to 55% of their weight in water and slowly release it under the plant's demand.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] This property can prevent root rot and moderate drought cycles.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] Zeolites have some veterinary applications, with clinoptilolite approved in the EU as an additive for cattle feed.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] It acts primarily as a detoxifying agent in the gut, where is can absorb undesirable species via ion-exchange before being excreted.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] For instance, nitrate fertilisers are water soluble and prolonged exposure by dairy cattle is known to impair protein metabolism and glucose utilization.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] Clinoptilolite adsorbs nitrate ions with good selectivity, allowing it to reduce these ill effects.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] Zeolites have been studied for human medical applications, particularly for bowel conditions.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] There are no approved medical uses for zeolites as of 2024.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] Regardless, they are widely marketed as dietary supplements.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] Computer calculations have predicted that millions of hypothetical zeolite structures are possible.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] However, only 232 of these structures have been discovered and synthesized so far.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] Many scientists studying zeolite question why only this small fraction of possibilities are observed.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] One explanation is that certain frameworks may be inaccessible, as nucleation cannot occur because more stable and energetically favorable zeolites will form.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] Post-synthetic modification has been used to combat this issue with the ADOR method, A theory of crystallization via solute pre-nucleation clusters was developed.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] Investigation of zeolite crystallization in hydrated silicate ionic liquids (HSIL) has shown that zeolites can nucleate via the condensation of ion-paired pre-nucleation clusters.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] Fibrous zeolites such as Erionite have been linked to lung cancer mesothelioma.
[src:heterogeneous-catalysis/zeolite] Other possible asbestiform zeolites with ongoing research (or more research needed) into their possible toxicty include: Ferrierite (leading candidate for toxicity due to being very similar chemically and habit as erionite), Mordenite, Mesolite Thomsonite, Natrolite, and Scolecite.
